# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: integrity-rtos
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] The term "avionics" was coined in 1949 by Philip J.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] Klass, senior editor at *Aviation Week & Space Technology* magazine as a portmanteau of "**aviation electronics**".
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] Radio communication was first used in aircraft just prior to World War I.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] The first airborne radios were in zeppelins, but the military sparked development of light radio sets that could be carried by heavier-than-air craft, so that aerial reconnaissance biplanes could report their observations immediately in case they were shot down.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] The first experimental radio transmission from an airplane was conducted by the U.S.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] The first aircraft radios transmitted by radiotelegraphy.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] They required a two-seat aircraft with a second crewman who operated a telegraph key to spell out messages in Morse code.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] During World War I, amplitude modulation voice two way radio sets were made possible in 1917 (see TM (triode)) by the development of the triode vacuum tube, which were simple enough that the pilot in a single seat aircraft could use it while flying.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] Radar, the central technology used today in aircraft navigation and air traffic control, was developed by several nations, mainly in secret, as an air defense system in the 1930s during the runup to World War II.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] Many modern avionics have their origins in World War II wartime developments.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] For example, autopilot systems that are commonplace today began as specialized systems to help bomber planes fly steadily enough to hit precision targets from high altitudes.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] Britain's 1940 decision to share its radar technology with its U.S. ally, particularly the magnetron vacuum tube, in the famous Tizard Mission, significantly shortened the war.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] Modern avionics is a substantial portion of military aircraft spending.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] Aircraft like the F-15E and the now retired F-14 have roughly 20 percent of their budget spent on avionics.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] Most modern helicopters now have budget splits of 60/40 in favour of avionics.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] The civilian market has also seen a growth in cost of avionics.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] Flight control systems (fly-by-wire) and new navigation needs brought on by tighter airspaces, have pushed up development costs.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] The major change has been the recent boom in consumer flying.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] As more people begin to use planes as their primary method of transportation, more elaborate methods of controlling aircraft safely in these high restrictive airspaces have been invented.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] Avionics plays a heavy role in modernization initiatives like the Federal Aviation Administration's (FAA) Next Generation Air Transportation System project in the United States and the Single European Sky ATM Research (SESAR) initiative in Europe.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] The cockpit or, in larger aircraft, under the cockpit of an aircraft or in a movable nosecone, is a typical location for avionic bay equipment, including control, monitoring, communication, navigation, weather, and anti-collision systems.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] The majority of aircraft power their avionics using 14- or 28‑volt DC electrical systems; however, larger, more sophisticated aircraft (such as airliners or military combat aircraft) have AC systems operating at 115 volts 400 Hz, AC.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] International standards for avionics equipment are prepared by the Airlines Electronic Engineering Committee and published by ARINC.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] Communications connect the flight deck to the ground and the flight deck to the passengers.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] On‑board communications are provided by public-address systems and aircraft intercoms.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] The VHF aviation communication system works on the airband of 118.000 MHz to 136.975 MHz.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] Each channel is spaced from the adjacent ones by 8.33 kHz in Europe, 25 kHz elsewhere.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] VHF is also used for line of sight communication such as aircraft-to-aircraft and aircraft-to-ATC.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] Amplitude modulation is used, and the conversation is performed in simplex mode.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] Aircraft communication can also take place using HF (especially for trans-oceanic flights) or satellite communication.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] Air navigation is the determination of position and direction on or above the surface of the Earth.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] Avionics can use satellite navigation systems (such as GPS, WAAS, EGNOS and GBAS/LAAS), inertial navigation system (INS), ground-based radio navigation systems (such as VOR or LORAN), or any combination thereof.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] Some navigation systems such as GPS calculate the position automatically and display it to the flight crew on moving map displays.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] Older ground-based Navigation systems such as VOR or LORAN requires a pilot or navigator to plot the intersection of signals on a paper map to determine an aircraft's location; modern systems calculate the position automatically and display it to the flight crew on moving map displays.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] The first hints of glass cockpits emerged in the 1970s when flight-worthy cathode ray tube (CRT) screens began to replace electromechanical displays, gauges and instruments.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] A "glass" cockpit refers to the use of computer monitors instead of gauges and other analog displays.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] Aircraft were getting progressively more displays, dials and information dashboards that eventually competed for space and pilot attention.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] In the 1970s, the average aircraft had more than 100 cockpit instruments and controls.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] Glass cockpits started to come into being with the Gulfstream G‑IV private jet in 1985.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] One of the key challenges in glass cockpits is to balance how much control is automated and how much the pilot should do manually.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] Generally they try to automate flight operations while keeping the pilot constantly informed.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] Aircraft have means of automatically controlling flight.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] Autopilot was first invented by Lawrence Sperry during World War I to fly bomber planes steady enough to hit accurate targets from 25,000 feet.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] When it was first adopted by the U.S. military, a Honeywell engineer sat in the back seat with bolt cutters to disconnect the autopilot in case of emergency.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] Nowadays most commercial planes are equipped with aircraft flight control systems in order to reduce pilot error and workload at landing or takeoff.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] The first simple commercial auto-pilots were used to control heading and altitude and had limited authority on things like thrust and flight control surfaces.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] In helicopters, auto-stabilization was used in a similar way.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] The first systems were electromechanical.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] The advent of fly-by-wire and electro-actuated flight surfaces (rather than the traditional hydraulic) has increased safety.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] As with displays and instruments, critical devices that were electro-mechanical had a finite life.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] With safety critical systems, the software is very strictly tested.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] Fuel Quantity Indication System (FQIS) monitors the amount of fuel aboard.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] Using various sensors, such as capacitance tubes, temperature sensors, densitometers & level sensors, the FQIS computer calculates the mass of fuel remaining on board.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] Fuel Control and Monitoring System (FCMS) reports fuel remaining on board in a similar manner, but, by controlling pumps & valves, also manages fuel transfers around various tanks.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] To supplement air traffic control, most large transport aircraft and many smaller ones use a traffic alert and collision avoidance system (TCAS), which can detect the location of nearby aircraft, and provide instructions for avoiding a midair collision.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] Smaller aircraft may use simpler traffic alerting systems such as TPAS, which are passive (they do not actively interrogate the transponders of other aircraft) and do not provide advisories for conflict resolution.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] To help avoid controlled flight into terrain (CFIT), aircraft use systems such as ground-proximity warning systems (GPWS), which use radar altimeters as a key element.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] One of the major weaknesses of GPWS is the lack of "look-ahead" information, because it only provides altitude above terrain "look-down".
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] In order to overcome this weakness, modern aircraft use a terrain awareness warning system (TAWS).
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] Commercial aircraft cockpit data recorders, commonly known as "black boxes", store flight information and audio from the cockpit.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] They are often recovered from an aircraft after a crash to determine control settings and other parameters during the incident.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] Weather systems such as weather radar (typically Arinc 708 on commercial aircraft) and lightning detectors are important for aircraft flying at night or in instrument meteorological conditions, where it is not possible for pilots to see the weather ahead.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] Heavy precipitation (as sensed by radar) or severe turbulence (as sensed by lightning activity) are both indications of strong convective activity and severe turbulence, and weather systems allow pilots to deviate around these areas.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] Lightning detectors like the Stormscope or Strikefinder have become inexpensive enough that they are practical for light aircraft.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] In addition to radar and lightning detection, observations and extended radar pictures (such as NEXRAD) are now available through satellite data connections, allowing pilots to see weather conditions far beyond the range of their own in-flight systems.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] Modern displays allow weather information to be integrated with moving maps, terrain, and traffic onto a single screen, greatly simplifying navigation.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] Modern weather systems also include wind shear and turbulence detection and terrain and traffic warning systems.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] In‑plane weather avionics are especially popular in Africa, India, and other countries where air-travel is a growing market, but ground support is not as well developed.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] There has been a progression towards centralized control of the multiple complex systems fitted to aircraft, including engine monitoring and management.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] Health and usage monitoring systems (HUMS) are integrated with aircraft management computers to give maintainers early warnings of parts that will need replacement.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] The integrated modular avionics concept proposes an integrated architecture with application software portable across an assembly of common hardware modules.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] It has been used in fourth generation jet fighters and the latest generation of airliners.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] Military aircraft have been designed either to deliver a weapon or to be the eyes and ears of other weapon systems.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] The vast array of sensors available to the military is used for whatever tactical means required.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] As with aircraft management, the bigger sensor platforms (like the E‑3D, JSTARS, ASTOR, Nimrod MRA4, Merlin HM Mk 1) have mission-management computers.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] Police and EMS aircraft also carry sophisticated tactical sensors.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] While aircraft communications provide the backbone for safe flight, the tactical systems are designed to withstand the rigors of the battlefield.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] UHF, VHF Tactical (30–88 MHz) and SatCom systems combined with ECCM methods, and cryptography secure the communications.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] Data links such as Link 11, 16, 22 and BOWMAN, JTRS and even TETRA provide the means of transmitting data (such as images, targeting information etc.).
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] Airborne radar was one of the first tactical sensors.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] The benefit of altitude providing range has meant a significant focus on airborne radar technologies.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] Radars include airborne early warning, anti-submarine warfare, and even weather radar (Arinc 708) and ground tracking/proximity radar.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] The military uses radar in fast jets to help pilots fly at low levels.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] While the civil market has had weather radar for a while, there are strict rules about using it to navigate the aircraft.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] Dipping sonar fitted to a range of military helicopters allows the helicopter to protect shipping assets from submarines or surface threats.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] Maritime support aircraft can drop active and passive sonar devices (sonobuoys) and these are also used to determine the location of enemy submarines.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] Electro-optic systems include devices such as the head-up display (HUD), forward looking infrared (FLIR), infrared search and track and other passive infrared devices (Passive infrared sensor).
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] These are all used to provide imagery and information to the flight crew.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] This imagery is used for everything from search and rescue to navigational aids and target acquisition.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] Electronic support measures and defensive aids systems are used extensively to gather information about threats or possible threats.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] They can be used to launch devices (in some cases automatically) to counter direct threats against the aircraft.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] They are also used to determine the state of a threat and identify it.
[src:integrity-rtos/avionics] The avionics systems in military, commercial and advanced models of civilian aircraft are interconnected using an avionics databus.
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] The **Common Criteria for Information Technology Security Evaluation**, or simply **Common Criteria** (**CC**), is an information security standard.
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] Common Criteria is a framework in which computer system users can *specify* their security *functional* and *assurance* requirements (SFRs and SARs, respectively) in a Security Target (ST), and may be taken from Protection Profiles (PPs).
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] Vendors can then *implement* or make claims about the security attributes of their products, and testing laboratories can *evaluate* the products to determine if they actually meet the claims.
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] In other words, Common Criteria provides assurance that the process of specification, implementation and evaluation of a computer security product has been conducted in a rigorous and standard and repeatable manner at a level that is commensurate with the target environment for use.
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] Common Criteria maintains a list of certified products, including operating systems, access control systems, databases, and key management systems.
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] Common Criteria evaluations are performed on computer security products and systems.
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] the product or system that is the subject of the evaluation.
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] The evaluation serves to validate claims made about the target.
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] ) relevant to that user for a particular purpose.
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] Product vendors can choose to implement products that comply with one or more PPs, and have their products evaluated against those PPs.
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] In such a case, a PP may serve as a template for the product's ST (Security Target, as defined below), or the authors of the ST will at least ensure that all requirements in relevant PPs also appear in the target's ST document.
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] Customers looking for particular types of products can focus on those certified against the PP that meets their requirements.
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] The ST may claim conformance with one or more PPs.
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] The TOE is evaluated against the SFRs (Security Functional Requirements.
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] Again, see below) established in its ST, no more and no less.
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] This allows vendors to tailor the evaluation to accurately match the intended capabilities of their product.
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] management system, and that different firewalls may in fact be evaluated against completely different lists of requirements.
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] The ST is usually published so that potential customers may determine the specific security features that have been certified by the evaluation.
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] The Common Criteria presents a standard catalogue of such functions.
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] The list of SFRs can vary from one evaluation to the next, even if two targets are the same type of product.
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] Although Common Criteria does not prescribe any SFRs to be included in an ST, it identifies dependencies where the correct operation of one function (such as the ability to limit access according to roles) is dependent on another (such as the ability to identify individual roles).
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] descriptions of the measures taken during development and evaluation of the product to assure compliance with the claimed security functionality.
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] For example, an evaluation may require that all source code is kept in a change management system, or that full functional testing is performed.
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] The Common Criteria provides a catalogue of these, and the requirements may vary from one evaluation to the next.
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] The requirements for particular targets or types of products are documented in the ST and PP, respectively.
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] the numerical rating describing the depth and rigor of an evaluation.
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] Each EAL corresponds to a package of security assurance requirements (SARs, see above) which covers the complete development of a product, with a given level of strictness.
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] Common Criteria lists seven levels, with EAL 1 being the most basic (and therefore cheapest to implement and evaluate) and EAL 7 being the most stringent (and most expensive).
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] Normally, an ST or PP author will not select assurance requirements individually but choose one of these packages, possibly 'augmenting' requirements in a few areas with requirements from a higher level.
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] So far, most PPs and most evaluated STs/certified products have been for IT components (e.g., firewalls, operating systems, smart cards).
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] Common Criteria certification is sometimes specified for IT procurement.
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] Other standards containing, e.g., interoperation, system management, user training, supplement CC and other product standards.
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] Examples include the ISO/IEC 27002 and the German IT baseline protection.
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] Details of cryptographic implementation within the TOE are outside the scope of the CC.
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] Instead, national standards, like FIPS 140-2, give the specifications for cryptographic modules, and various standards specify the cryptographic algorithms in use.
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] More recently, PP authors are including cryptographic requirements for CC evaluations that would typically be covered by FIPS 140-2 evaluations, broadening the bounds of the CC through scheme-specific interpretations.
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] Some national evaluation schemes are phasing out EAL-based evaluations and only accept products for evaluation that claim strict conformance with an approved PP.
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] The United States currently only allows PP-based evaluations.
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] CC was produced by unifying these pre-existing standards, predominantly so that companies selling computer products for the government market (mainly for Defence or Intelligence use) would only need to have them evaluated against one set of standards.
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] The CC was developed by the governments of Canada, France, Germany, the Netherlands, the UK, and the U.S.
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] All testing laboratories must comply with ISO/IEC 17025, and certification bodies will normally be approved against ISO/IEC 17065.
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] Characteristics of these organizations were examined and presented at ICCC 10.
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] As well as the Common Criteria standard, there is also a sub-treaty level Common Criteria MRA (Mutual Recognition Arrangement), whereby each party thereto recognizes evaluations against the Common Criteria standard done by other parties.
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] Originally signed in 1998 by Canada, France, Germany, the United Kingdom and the United States, Australia and New Zealand joined 1999, followed by Finland, Greece, Israel, Italy, the Netherlands, Norway and Spain in 2000.
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] The Arrangement has since been renamed **Common Criteria Recognition Arrangement** (**CCRA**) and membership continues to expand.
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] Within the CCRA only evaluations up to EAL 2 are mutually recognized (Including augmentation with flaw remediation).
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] The European countries within the SOGIS-MRA typically recognize higher EALs as well.
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] Evaluations at EAL5 and above tend to involve the security requirements of the host nation's government.
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] In September 2012, a majority of members of the CCRA produced a vision statement whereby mutual recognition of CC evaluated products will be lowered to EAL 2 (Including augmentation with flaw remediation).
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] Further, this vision indicates a move away from assurance levels altogether and evaluations will be confined to conformance with Protection Profiles that have no stated assurance level.
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] This will be achieved through technical working groups developing worldwide PPs, and as yet a transition period has not been fully determined.
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] On July 2, 2014, a new CCRA was ratified per the goals outlined within the 2012 vision statement.
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] Common Criteria certification cannot guarantee security, but it can ensure that claims about the security attributes of the evaluated product were independently verified.
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] In other words, products evaluated against a Common Criteria standard exhibit a clear chain of evidence that the process of specification, implementation, and evaluation has been conducted in a rigorous and standard manner.
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] Various Microsoft Windows versions, including Windows Server 2003 and Windows XP, have been certified, but security patches to address security vulnerabilities are still getting published by Microsoft for these Windows systems.
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] This is possible because the process of obtaining a Common Criteria certification allows a vendor to restrict the analysis to certain security features and to make certain assumptions about the operating environment and the strength of threats faced by the product in that environment.
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] Additionally, the CC recognizes a need to limit the scope of evaluation in order to provide cost-effective and useful security certifications, such that evaluated products are examined to a level of detail specified by the assurance level or PP.
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] Evaluations activities are therefore only performed to a certain depth, use of time, and resources and offer reasonable assurance for the intended environment.
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] This assumption is contained in the Controlled Access Protection Profile (CAPP) to which their products adhere.
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] Based on this and other assumptions, which may not be realistic for the common use of general-purpose operating systems, the claimed security functions of the Windows products are evaluated.
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] Thus they should only be considered secure in the assumed, specified circumstances, also known as the *evaluated configuration*.
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] Whether you run Microsoft Windows in the precise evaluated configuration or not, you should apply Microsoft's security patches for the vulnerabilities in Windows as they continue to appear.
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] If any of these security vulnerabilities are exploitable in the product's evaluated configuration, the product's Common Criteria certification should be voluntarily withdrawn by the vendor.
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] Alternatively, the vendor should re-evaluate the product to include the application of patches to fix the security vulnerabilities within the evaluated configuration.
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] Failure by the vendor to take either of these steps would result in involuntary withdrawal of the product's certification by the certification body of the country in which the product was evaluated.
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] The certified Microsoft Windows versions remain at EAL4+ without including the application of any Microsoft security vulnerability patches in their evaluated configuration.
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] This shows both the limitation and strength of an evaluated configuration.
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] In August 2007, *Government Computing News* (GCN) columnist William Jackson critically examined Common Criteria methodology and its US implementation by the Common Criteria Evaluation and Validation Scheme (CCEVS).
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] In the column executives from the security industry, researchers, and representatives from the National Information Assurance Partnership (NIAP) were interviewed.
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] In a 2006 research paper, computer specialist David A.
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] Wheeler suggested that the Common Criteria process discriminates against free and open-source software (FOSS)-centric organizations and development models.
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] Common Criteria assurance requirements tend to be inspired by the traditional waterfall software development methodology.
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] In contrast, much FOSS software is produced using modern agile paradigms.
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] Although some have argued that both paradigms do not align well, others have attempted to reconcile both paradigms.
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] In 2017, the ROCA vulnerability was found in a list of Common Criteria certified smart card products.
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] Throughout the lifetime of CC, it has not been universally adopted even by the creator nations, with, in particular, cryptographic approvals being handled separately, such as by the Canadian / US implementation of FIPS-140, and the CESG Assisted Products Scheme (CAPS) in the UK.
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] In early 2011, NSA/CSS published a paper by Chris Salter, which proposed a Protection Profile oriented approach towards evaluation.
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] In this approach, communities of interest form around technology types which in turn develop protection profiles that define the evaluation methodology for the technology type.
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] The objective is a more robust evaluation.
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] There is some concern that this may have a negative impact on mutual recognition.
[src:integrity-rtos/common-criteria] In Sept of 2012, the Common Criteria published a Vision Statement implementing to a large extent Chris Salter's thoughts from the previous year.
[src:integrity-rtos/green-hills-software] In the 1990s, Green Hills Software and Wind River Systems, both makers of embedded system software development tools, entered into a 99-year agreement to cooperatively support customers using products from both companies.
[src:integrity-rtos/green-hills-software] The agreement was terminated after a lawsuit in 2005.
[src:integrity-rtos/green-hills-software] After parting ways, Wind River publicly embraced Linux and open-source software while Green Hills initiated a public relations campaign decrying the use of open-source software in projects related to national security.
[src:integrity-rtos/green-hills-software] In November 2008, it was announced that a commercialized version of Integrity 178-B would be offered to the private sector by Integrity Global Security, a subsidiary of Green Hills Software.
[src:integrity-rtos/green-hills-software] On March 27, 2012, a contract was announced between Green Hills Software and Nintendo.
[src:integrity-rtos/green-hills-software] This designates MULTI as the official integrated development environment and toolchain for Nintendo and its licensed developers to program the Wii U video game console.
[src:integrity-rtos/green-hills-software] On February 25, 2014, it was announced that the operating system Integrity had been chosen by Urban Aeronautics for their AirMule flying car unmanned aerial vehicle (UAV), since renamed the Tactical Robotics Cormorant.
[src:integrity-rtos/green-hills-software] Integrity is a POSIX real-time operating system (RTOS).
[src:integrity-rtos/green-hills-software] An Integrity variant, named Integrity-178B, was certified to Common Criteria Evaluation Assurance Level (EAL) 6+, High Robustness in November 2008.
[src:integrity-rtos/green-hills-software] Micro Velosity (stylized as *μ-velOSity*) is a real-time microkernel for resource-constrained devices.
[src:integrity-rtos/green-hills-software] Green Hills produces compilers for the programming languages C, C++, Fortran, and Ada.
[src:integrity-rtos/green-hills-software] They are cross-platform, for 32- and 64-bit microprocessors, including RISC-V, ARM, Blackfin, ColdFire, MIPS, PowerPC, SuperH, StarCore, x86, V850, and XScale.
[src:integrity-rtos/green-hills-software] MULTI is an integrated development environment (IDE) for the programming languages C, C++, Embedded C++ (EC++), and Ada, aimed at embedded engineers.
[src:integrity-rtos/green-hills-software] TimeMachine is a set of tools for optimizing and debugging C and C++ software.
[src:integrity-rtos/green-hills-software] TimeMachine (introduced 2003) supports reverse debugging, a feature that later also became available in the free GNU Debugger (GDB) 7.0 (2009).
[src:integrity-rtos/integrity-operating-system] INTEGRITY is POSIX-certified and intended for use in embedded systems of 32-bits or 64-bits.
[src:integrity-rtos/integrity-operating-system] Supported computer architectures include variants of: ARM, Blackfin, ColdFire, MIPS, PowerPC, XScale, and x86.
[src:integrity-rtos/integrity-operating-system] INTEGRITY is supported by popular SSL/TLS libraries such as wolfSSL.
[src:integrity-rtos/integrity-operating-system] INTEGRITY-178B is the DO-178B–compliant version of INTEGRITY.
[src:integrity-rtos/integrity-operating-system] It is used in several military jets such as the B-2, F-16, F-22, and F-35, and the commercial aircraft Airbus A380.
[src:integrity-rtos/integrity-operating-system] Its kernel design guarantees bounded computing times by eliminating features such as dynamic memory allocation.
[src:integrity-rtos/integrity-operating-system] The auditing and security engineering abilities have allowed it to obtain the Evaluation Assurance Level (EAL) 6 rating by the National Security Agency (NSA).
[src:integrity-rtos/integrity-operating-system] The Target of Evaluation (TOE) Architecture in the Security Target for the evaluation excludes components such as those for file system and networking, from the definition of the TOE, focusing almost solely on the core kernel.
[src:integrity-rtos/integrity-operating-system] Other operating systems, such as Windows, macOS or Linux, though evaluated at lower levels of assurance, generally include these abilities within their TOE.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] A **real-time operating system** (**RTOS**) is an operating system (OS) for real-time computing applications that processes data and events that have critically defined time constraints.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] An RTOS mainly targets resource constrained devices like microcontrollers.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] It is distinct from a time-sharing operating system, such as Unix, which manages the sharing of system resources with a scheduler, data buffers, or fixed task prioritization in multitasking or multiprogramming environments.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] All operations must verifiably complete within given time and resource constraints or else the RTOS will fail safe.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Real-time operating systems are event-driven and preemptive, meaning the OS can monitor the relevant priority of competing tasks, and make changes to the task priority.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] A key characteristic of an RTOS is the level of its consistency concerning the amount of time it takes to accept and complete an application's task; the variability is "jitter".
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] The chief design goal is not high throughput, but rather a guarantee of a soft or hard performance category.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] An RTOS that can usually or generally meet a deadline is a soft real-time OS, but if it can meet a deadline deterministically it is a hard real-time OS.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] An RTOS has an advanced algorithm for scheduling.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Scheduler flexibility enables a wider, computer-system orchestration of process priorities, but a real-time OS is more frequently dedicated to a narrow set of applications.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Key factors in a real-time OS are minimal interrupt latency and minimal thread switching latency; a real-time OS is valued more for how quickly or how predictably it can respond than for the amount of work it can perform in a given period of time.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Time sharing designs switch tasks more often than strictly needed, but give smoother multitasking, giving the illusion that a process or user has sole use of a machine.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Early CPU designs needed many cycles to switch tasks during which the CPU could do nothing else useful.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Because switching took so long, early OSes tried to minimize wasting CPU time by avoiding unnecessary task switching.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Blocked (waiting for an event, I/O for example).
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Most tasks are blocked or ready most of the time because generally only one task can run at a time per CPU core.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] The number of items in the ready queue can vary greatly, depending on the number of tasks the system needs to perform and the type of scheduler that the system uses.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] On simpler non-preemptive but still multitasking systems, a task has to give up its time on the CPU to other tasks, which can cause the ready queue to have a greater number of overall tasks in the ready to be executed state (resource starvation).
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] If there are never more than a few tasks on the ready list, then a doubly linked list of ready tasks is likely optimal.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] If the ready list usually contains only a few tasks but occasionally contains more, then the list should be sorted by priority, so that finding the highest priority task to run does not require traversing the list.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Instead, inserting a task requires walking the list.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] During this search, preemption should not be inhibited.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Long critical sections should be divided into smaller pieces.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] If an interrupt occurs that makes a high priority task ready during the insertion of a low priority task, that high priority task can be inserted and run immediately before the low priority task is inserted.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] The critical response time, sometimes called the flyback time, is the time it takes to queue a new ready task and restore the state of the highest priority task to running.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] In a well-designed RTOS, readying a new task will take 3 to 20 instructions per ready-queue entry, and restoration of the highest-priority ready task will take 5 to 30 instructions.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] In advanced systems, real-time tasks share computing resources with many non-real-time tasks, and the ready list can be arbitrarily long.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] In such systems, a scheduler ready list implemented as a linked list would be inadequate.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] A multitasking operating system like Unix is poor at real-time tasks.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] The scheduler gives the highest priority to jobs with the lowest demand on the computer, so there is no way to ensure that a time-critical job will have access to enough resources.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Multitasking systems must manage sharing data and hardware resources among multiple tasks.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] It is usually unsafe for two tasks to access the same specific data or hardware resource simultaneously.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] General-purpose operating systems usually do not allow user programs to mask (disable) interrupts, because the user program could control the CPU for as long as it is made to.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Some modern CPUs do not allow user mode code to disable interrupts as such control is considered a key operating system resource.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Many embedded systems and RTOSs, however, allow the application itself to run in kernel mode for greater system call efficiency and also to permit the application to have greater control of the operating environment without requiring OS intervention.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] On single-processor systems, an application running in kernel mode and masking interrupts is the lowest overhead method to prevent simultaneous access to a shared resource.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] While interrupts are masked and the current task does not make a blocking OS call, the current task has *exclusive* use of the CPU since no other task or interrupt can take control, so the critical section is protected.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] When the task exits its critical section, it must unmask interrupts; pending interrupts, if any, will then execute.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Temporarily masking interrupts should only be done when the longest path through the critical section is shorter than the desired maximum interrupt latency.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Typically this method of protection is used only when the critical section is just a few instructions and contains no loops.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] This method is ideal for protecting hardware bit-mapped registers when the bits are controlled by different tasks.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] When the shared resource must be reserved without blocking all other tasks (such as waiting for Flash memory to be written), it is better to use mechanisms also available on general-purpose operating systems, such as a mutex and OS-supervised interprocess messaging.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Such mechanisms involve system calls, and usually invoke the OS's dispatcher code on exit, so they typically take hundreds of CPU instructions to execute, while masking interrupts may take as few as one instruction on some processors.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] A (non-recursive) mutex is either **locked** or unlocked.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] When a task has locked the mutex, all other tasks must wait for the mutex to be unlocked by its *owner* - the original thread.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] A task may set a timeout on its wait for a mutex.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] There are several well-known problems with mutex based designs such as priority inversion and deadlocks.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] In priority inversion a high priority task waits because a low priority task has a mutex, but the lower priority task is not given CPU time to finish its work.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] A typical solution is to have the task that owns a mutex 'inherit' the priority of the highest waiting task.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] But this simple approach gets more complex when there are multiple levels of waiting: task *A* waits for a mutex locked by task *B*, which waits for a mutex locked by task *C*.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Handling multiple levels of inheritance causes other code to run in high priority context and thus can cause starvation of medium-priority threads.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] In a deadlock, two or more tasks lock mutex without timeouts and then wait forever for the other task's mutex, creating a cyclic dependency.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] The simplest deadlock scenario occurs when two tasks alternately lock two mutex, but in the opposite order.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Deadlock is prevented by careful design.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] The other approach to resource sharing is for tasks to send messages in an organized message passing scheme.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] In this paradigm, the resource is managed directly by only one task.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] When another task wants to interrogate or manipulate the resource, it sends a message to the managing task.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Although their real-time behavior is less crisp than semaphore systems, simple message-based systems avoid most protocol deadlock hazards, and are generally better-behaved than semaphore systems.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] However, problems like those of semaphores are possible.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Priority inversion can occur when a task is working on a low-priority message and ignores a higher-priority message (or a message originating indirectly from a high priority task) in its incoming message queue.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Protocol deadlocks can occur when two or more tasks wait for each other to send response messages.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Since an interrupt handler blocks the highest priority task from running, and since real-time operating systems are designed to keep thread latency to a minimum, interrupt handlers are typically kept as short as possible.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] The interrupt handler defers all interaction with the hardware if possible; typically all that is necessary is to acknowledge or disable the interrupt (so that it won't occur again when the interrupt handler returns) and notify a task that work needs to be done.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] This can be done by unblocking a driver task through releasing a semaphore, setting a flag or sending a message.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] A scheduler often provides the ability to unblock a task from interrupt handler context.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] An OS maintains catalogues of objects it manages such as threads, mutexes, memory, and so on.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Updates to this catalogue must be strictly controlled.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] For this reason, it can be problematic when an interrupt handler calls an OS function while the application is in the act of also doing so.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] The OS function called from an interrupt handler could find the object database to be in an inconsistent state because of the application's update.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] There are two major approaches to deal with this problem: the unified architecture and the segmented architecture.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] RTOSs implementing the unified architecture solve the problem by simply disabling interrupts while the internal catalogue is updated.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] The downside of this is that interrupt latency increases, potentially losing interrupts.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] The segmented architecture does not make direct OS calls but delegates the OS related work to a separate handler.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] This handler runs at a higher priority than any thread but lower than the interrupt handlers.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] The advantage of this architecture is that it adds very few cycles to interrupt latency.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] As a result, OSes which implement the segmented architecture are more predictable and can deal with higher interrupt rates compared to the unified architecture.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Similarly, the System Management Mode on x86 compatible hardware can take a lot of time before it returns control to the operating system.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Memory allocation is more critical in a real-time operating system than in other operating systems.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] First, for stability there cannot be memory leaks (memory that is allocated but not freed after use).
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] The device should work indefinitely, without ever needing a reboot.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] For this reason, dynamic memory allocation is frowned upon.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Whenever possible, all required memory allocation is specified statically at compile time.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Another reason to avoid dynamic memory allocation is memory fragmentation.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] With frequent allocation and releasing of small chunks of memory, a situation may occur where available memory is divided into several sections and the RTOS cannot allocate a large enough continuous block of memory, although there is enough free memory.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Secondly, speed of allocation is important.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] A standard memory allocation scheme scans a linked list of indeterminate length to find a suitable free memory block, which is unacceptable in a RTOS since memory allocation has to occur within a certain amount of time.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] Because mechanical disks have much longer and more unpredictable response times, swapping to disk files is not used for the same reasons as RAM allocation discussed above.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] The simple fixed-size-blocks algorithm works quite well for simple embedded systems because of its low overhead.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] While all RTOSes are able to run on microcontrollers they have ports for, some RTOSes like Zephyr are capable of abstracting even further a number of device drivers like External Flash, I2C devices or internal peripherals like UART commands and sleep modes.
[src:integrity-rtos/real-time-operating-system] This helps offload the need for a developer to create drivers and instead a set of APIs are given for unsupported drivers to be ported over while supported ones are ready for use within the application code.
[src:integrity-rtos/separation-kernel] A **separation kernel** is a type of security kernel used to simulate a distributed environment.
[src:integrity-rtos/separation-kernel] The concept was introduced by John Rushby in a 1981 paper.
[src:integrity-rtos/separation-kernel] A variant of the separation kernel, the partitioning kernel, has gained acceptance in the commercial aviation community as a way of consolidating multiple functions onto a single processor, perhaps of mixed criticality.
[src:integrity-rtos/separation-kernel] Commercial real-time operating system products in this genre have been used by aircraft manufacturers for safety-critical avionics applications.
[src:integrity-rtos/separation-kernel] In 2007 the Information Assurance Directorate of the U.S.
[src:integrity-rtos/separation-kernel] National Security Agency (NSA) published the Separation Kernel Protection Profile (SKPP), a security requirements specification for separation kernels suitable to be used in the most hostile threat environments.
[src:integrity-rtos/separation-kernel] The SKPP describes, in Common Criteria parlance, a class of modern products that provide the foundational properties of Rushby's conceptual separation kernel.
[src:integrity-rtos/separation-kernel] It defines the security functional and assurance requirements for the construction and evaluation of separation kernels while yet providing some latitude in the choices available to developers.
[src:integrity-rtos/separation-kernel] In 2011, the Information Assurance Directorate sunset the SKPP.
[src:integrity-rtos/separation-kernel] The seL4 microkernel has a formal proof of concept that it can be configured as a separation kernel.
[src:integrity-rtos/separation-kernel] The enforced continuance of information along with this implies it is an elevated level example of assurance.
[src:integrity-rtos/separation-kernel] The Muen separation kernel is also a formally verified open source separation kernel for x86 machines.
